  "prompt": "How are bra sizes measured?",
  "response": "Bra sizes are typically measured using two key dimensions: the band size and the cup size. Here's a step-by-step guide on how to measure them:\n\n### Band Size (Underbust Measurement)\n1. **Measure the Underbust**: Wrap a measuring tape around your ribcage, right underneath your bust. Ensure the tape is parallel to the ground and snug but not tight. Note the measurement in inches.\n2. **Band Size Calculation**: Most sizing systems recommend rounding to the nearest even number, as band sizes are generally even numbers. For example, if your underbust measurement is 31.5 inches, you would round up to 32 inches.\n\n### Cup Size (Overbust Measurement)\n1. **Measure the Overbust**: Wrap the measuring tape around the fullest part of your bust, usually at nipple level. Make sure the tape is parallel to the ground and not too tight or too loose. Note this measurement in inches.\n2. **Cup Size Calculation**: Calculate the difference between the overbust measurement and the band measurement. Each inch difference typically corresponds to a cup size. For example:\n    - 1-inch difference = A cup\n    - 2-inch difference = B cup\n    - 3-inch difference = C cup\n    - 4-inch difference = D cup, and so on.\n\n### Example\n- **Underbust measurement**: 32 inches (band size)\n- **Overbust measurement**: 36 inches\n- **Difference**: 36 - 32 = 4 inches (D cup)\n- **Bra Size**: 32D\n\n### Sizing Variations\nPlease note that sizing may vary slightly between brands and countries. For instance, UK sizing uses a different labeling system compared to US sizing for larger cup sizes.\n\n### Additional Considerations\n- **Sister Sizes**: These are bras with different band sizes and cup sizes that have the same volume. For example, 34B and 32C are sister sizes.\n- **Fit and Comfort**: The measurement is a starting point; you may need to try on different sizes to find the best fit. Comfort and support are crucial.\n\nHaving the correct fit can make a significant difference in comfort and appearance, so it's worth spending time to get it right!",
